{{Other uses|Abram (disambiguation)}} {{Wiktionary|Abram|abram}}
'''Abram''' is a masculine [[given name]] of [[Biblical Hebrew]] origin,<ref name="Nikonov">Nikonov, p.&nbsp;96</ref> meaning ''exalted father''.<ref>[[New International Version|NIV]] translation of the Bible, footnote to {{bibleverse||Genesis|17:5|NIV}}</ref><ref name="Petrovsky">Petrovsky, p.&nbsp;35</ref> In the [[Bible]], it was originally the name of the first of the three Biblical patriarchs, who later became known as [[Abraham]].
==Russian name== The [[Russian language]] borrowed the name from [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Christianity, but its popularity, along with other Biblical first names, declined by the mid-19th century.<ref name="Nikonov" /> The forms used by the Russian Orthodox church were "{{lang|ru|Авраа́м}}" (''Avraam''),<ref name="Nikonov" /><ref name="Superanskaya">Superanskaya [1], p.&nbsp;20</ref> "{{lang|ru|Авраа́мий}}" (''Avraamy''),<ref name="Superanskaya" /> and "{{lang|ru|Авра́мий}}" (''Avramy''),<ref name="Superanskaya2">Superanskaya [2], p.&nbsp;30</ref> but "{{lang|ru|Абра́м}}" (''Abram'') remained a popular colloquial variant.<ref name="Nikonov" /><ref name="Petrovsky" /> Other colloquial forms included "{{lang|ru|Абра́мий}}" (''Abramy''),<ref name="Petrovsky" /> "{{lang|ru|Авра́м}}" (''Avram''),<ref name="Superanskaya2" /> and "{{lang|ru|Обра́м}}" (''Obram'').<ref name="Superanskaya2" /> Until the end of the 19th century, the official [[Synod]]al [[Menologium]] also included the form "{{lang|ru|Абраха́м}}" (''Abrakham'').<ref name="Superanskaya2a">Superanskaya [2], pp.&nbsp;23 and 30</ref>
The [[patronymic]]s derived from "Abram" are "{{lang|ru|Абра́мович}}" (''Abramovich''; masculine) and its colloquial form "{{lang|ru|Абра́мыч}}" (''Abramych''), and "{{lang|ru|Абра́мовна}}" (''Abramovna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The patronymics derived from "Abramy" are "{{lang|ru|Абра́миевич}}" (''Abramiyevich''; masculine) and "{{lang|ru|Абра́миевна}}" (''Abramiyevna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The patronymics derived from "Avraam" are "{{lang|ru|Авраа́мович}}" (''Avraamovich''; masculine) and "{{lang|ru|Авраа́мовна}}" (''Avraamovna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The patronymics derived from "Avraamy" are "{{lang|ru|Авраа́миевич}}" (''Avraamiyevich''; masculine) and "{{lang|ru|Авраа́миевна}}" (''Avraamiyevna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The patronymics derived from "Avram" are "{{lang|ru|Авра́мович}}" (''Avramovich''; masculine) and "{{lang|ru|Авра́мовна}}" (''Avramovna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The patronymics derived from "Avraamy" are "{{lang|ru|Авраа́миевич}}" (''Avraamiyevich''; masculine) and "{{lang|ru|Авраа́миевна}}" (''Avraamiyevna''; feminine).<ref name="Petrovsky" />
The [[diminutive]]s of "Avraam" and "Avraamy" include "{{lang|ru|Авраа́мка}}" (''Avraamka''), "{{lang|ru|Авра́мка}}" (''Avramka''), "{{lang|ru|Авраа́ха}}" (''Avraakha''), "{{lang|ru|Авра́ха}}" (''Avrakha''), "{{lang|ru|Авраа́ша}}" (''Avraasha''), and "{{lang|ru|Авра́ша}}" (''Avrasha'').<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The diminutives of "Abram" include "{{lang|ru|Абра́мка}}" (''Abraamka''), "{{lang|ru|Абра́ха}}" (''Abrakha''), and "{{lang|ru|Абра́ша}}" (''Abrasha'').<ref name="Petrovsky" /> The [[diminutive]]s of "Avram" include "{{lang|ru|Авра́мка}}" (''Avramka''), "{{lang|ru|Авра́ха}}" (''Avrakha''), "{{lang|ru|Авра́ша}}" (''Avrasha''), and "{{lang|ru|А́ва}}" (''Ava'').<ref name="Petrovsky" />
