'''Charles-François Lebrun, 1st [[Duc de Plaisance|duc de Plaisance]]''' (19 March 1739 &ndash; 16 June 1824), was a [[France|French]] statesman who served as [[French Consulate|Third Consul of the French Republic]] and was later created [[Grand Dignitaries of the French Empire|Arch-Treasurer]] and [[Nobility of the First French Empire|Prince of the Empire]] by [[Napoleon I]].

==Biography==

===''Ancien Régime''===
Born in [[Saint-Sauveur-Lendelin]] ([[Manche]]), after studies of [[philosophy]] at the ''[[Collège de Navarre]]'', he started his career during the ''[[Ancien Régime]]'', making his first appearance as a [[lawyer]] in [[Paris]] in 1762. He filled the posts of ''[[censeur du Roi]]'' (1766) and then [[Inspector General]] of the [[Crown land|Domains of the Crown]] (1768).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}}

During the early 1760s, Lebrun became a disciple of [[Charles de Secondat, baron de Montesquieu|Montesquieu]] and an admirer of the [[Constitution of the United Kingdom|British Constitution]], travelling through [[Southern Netherlands]], the [[Dutch Republic]], and finally to the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] (where he witnessed the debates in the [[Parliament of Great Britain|London Parliament]]).{{citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=none of facts this paragraph is mentioned in EB1911}}

He became one of [[List of Justice Ministers of France|Chancellor]] [[René Nicolas Charles Augustin de Maupeou|René Nicolas de Maupéou]]'s chief advisers, taking part in his struggle against the ''[[parlement]]s'' and sharing his downfall in 1774. Lebrun then devoted himself to literature, translating [[Torquato Tasso]]'s ''[[Jerusalem Delivered]]'' (1774) and the ''[[Iliad]]'' (1776). He retreated from public life to his property in [[Grillon]], attempting to live a life as envisaged by the ''[[philosophe]]'' [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]]. During the cabinet of [[Jacques Necker]], he was consulted on several occasions, but never appointed to high office.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}}

===Constituent Assembly and provincial politics===
[[File:Lebrun, Charles François.jpg|thumb|Charles-François Lebrun]]

At the outbreak of the [[French Revolution]] in 1789, he foresaw its importance in his volume ''La voix du Citoyen'', published the same year, and predicted the course which events would take. In the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]] and (after he took the ''[[Tennis Court Oath]]'') in the [[National Constituent Assembly (France)|National Constituent Assembly]], where he sat as deputy for the [[Estates of the realm|Third Estate]] in the [[bailiwick]] of [[Dourdan]], he professed [[Liberalism]] and proposed various financial laws, without affiliating to any particular faction.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}} A partisan of [[constitutional monarchy]] even after [[List of French monarchs|King]] [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]]'s [[flight to Varennes]] (June 1791), he became the target for the suspicions of the [[Jacobin Club]].{{citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=to cover facts from the last citation}}

After the voting of the [[French Constitution of 1791|1791 Constitution]], he was ineligible for the [[Legislative Assembly (France)|Legislative Assembly]] (like all former members of the Constituent Assembly), and became instead president of the directory of [[Seine-et-Oise]] ''[[Département in France|département]]''.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}}

Lebrun retired from this position on 7 August 1792, and again retired to Dourdan. Three days later, the [[10th of August (French Revolution)|storming of the Tuileries Palace]] signalled the move towards the establishment of the [[First French Republic|French Republic]] by the creation of the [[National Convention]]. Lebrun further aroused the indignation of republicans when he accepted to represent Dourdan in the [[electoral college]] of Seine-et-Oise which nominated deputies to the Convention.{{citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=all the facts in the paragraph}}

===Terror, Thermidor, and Directory===
A suspect during the [[Reign of Terror]], he was twice arrested: the first time in September 1793, liberated after the intervention of [[Joseph Augustin Crassous]] ([[Representatives on mission|representative on mission]] to Seine-et-Oise); the second time in June 1794 (paradoxically, on orders from the same Crassous) - threatened with the [[guillotine]], he was saved by a relative of his who stole his record of prosecution, thus causing a delay long enough for Lebrun to be saved by the [[Thermidorian Reaction]].{{citation needed|date=November 2018|reason=all the facts in the paragraph}}

In 1795, Lebrun was elected as a deputy to the [[French Directory]]'s [[Council of Ancients]] and,{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}} although a supporter of the [[House of Bourbon]], he voted against prosecutions of Jacobins, and showed himself in favour of national reconciliation.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}

===Consulate, Empire, and Restoration===

[[File:3consuls.jpg|thumb|The Three Consuls (Lebrun, right)]]
[[File:Histoire Naturelle 1810.jpg|thumbnail|''Histoire Naturelle'', 1810 - one of the paintings recently installed in the entrance of Herengracht 40 in Amsterdam, this one with the portrait of Charles-François LeBrun, Napoleon's governor of the Netherlands]]
[[Image:Herengracht40.JPG|thumb|Mansion of Lebrun on Herengracht 40, Amsterdam]]
[[Image:tombe lebrun.jpg|thumb|Tomb of Charles-François Lebrun]]

Lebrun was made [[Third Consul]] following [[Napoleon Bonaparte]]'s [[18 Brumaire|18 Brumaire coup]] in the Year VIII (9–10 November 1799; ''see [[French Consulate]]''). In this capacity, he took an active part in Napoleon's reorganization of the national finances and in the administration of France's ''départements''. He was made a member of the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]] in 1803, and in 1804, he was appointed [[Grand Dignitaries of the French Empire|Arch-Treasurer]] of the [[First French Empire|French Empire]]. From 1805 to 1806, he was [[governor-general]] of [[Liguria]], during which time he completed its annexation by France.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}}

He opposed Napoleon's restoration of the ''[[French nobility|noblesse]]'' and, in 1808, only reluctantly accepted the title of ''[[duc de Plaisance]]'' (Duke of [[Piacenza]]),{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}} a rare, nominal, but hereditary ''[[duché grand-fief]]'', extinguished in 1926.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} From 1811 to 1813, he served as governor-general of a part of the annexed [[Netherlands]], reorganizing its ''départements'' - [[Zuyderzée]] and [[Bouches-de-la-Meuse]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}} He was assisted by Antoine de Celles and [[Goswin de Stassart]].{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}

Although to a certain extent opposed to the [[autocracy]] of the Emperor, he was not in favor of his deposition, although he accepted the ''[[fait accompli]]'' of the [[Bourbon Restoration]] in April 1814. [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis XVIII]] made him a [[Peerage of France|Peer of France]], but during the subsequent [[Hundred Days]], he accepted from Napoleon the post of ''[[grand maître de l'Université]]''. As a consequence, he was suspended from the House of Peers when the Bourbons returned again in 1815, but was recalled in 1819. He died five years later in [[Sainte-Mesme]] (then in Seine-et-Oise, now in [[Yvelines]]).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=352}}

