'''Laura Kipnis''' (born 1956<ref>Peter Brooker, ''Modernism/Postmodernism'', Routledge, 2014, first published 1992, p. 250</ref>) is an American cultural critic and essayist. Her work focuses on [[Sexual Politics|sexual politics]], [[gender issues]], aesthetics, [[popular culture]], and [[pornography]]. She began her career as a [[video art]]ist, exploring similar themes in the form of video essays.<ref>http://www.vdb.org/artists/laura-kipnis</ref> She is professor of media studies at [[Northwestern University]] in the Department of Radio-TV-Film, where she teaches [[filmmaking]]. In recent years she has become known for debating [[sexual harassment]] policies in higher education.

==Career==
Kipnis was born in Chicago, Illinois. She earned a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] at the [[San Francisco Art Institute]] and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from [[Nova Scotia College of Art and Design]]. She also studied at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]] Independent Study Studio Program. She has received fellowships for her work from the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|Guggenheim Foundation]], the [[Rockefeller Foundation]], the Michigan Society of Fellows,<ref>http://societyoffellows.umich.edu/alumni-fellows/</ref> and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]]. She has been assistant professor, associate professor, and is now full professor at [[Northwestern University]].

==Work==
In her 2003 book ''Against Love: A Polemic'', a "ragingly witty yet contemplative look at the discontents of domestic and erotic relationships, Kipnis combines portions of the slashing sexual contrarianism of [[Norman Mailer|Mailer]], the scathing antidomestic wit of early [[Roseanne Barr]] and the coolly analytical aesthetics of early [[Susan Sontag|Sontag]]."<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-375-42189-1 ''Publisher's Weekly'' (30 June 2003).]</ref>

In 2010 she published ''How to Become a Scandal: Adventures in Bad Behavior'', which focused on scandal, including those of [[Eliot Spitzer]], [[Linda Tripp]], [[James Frey]], [[Sol Wachtler]], and [[Lisa Nowak]]; the book examined "the elaborate ways those transgressors reassure themselves that they are not bringing colossal ruin upon themselves, that their dalliances will never see the light of day".<ref>{{cite news| title=Laura Kipnis's "How to Become a Scandal" |work=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/09/24/AR2010092402261.html |first=Ellen|last=McCarthy|date=26 September 2010}}</ref> "What allows for scandal in Kipnis's schema is every individual's blind spot, "a little existential joke on humankind (or in some cases, a ticking time bomb) nestled at the core of every lonely consciousness...Ostensibly about scandal, her book is most memorable as a convincing case for the ultimate unknowability of the self".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Susan Dominus|title=They Did What?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/26/books/review/Dominus-t.html|work=New York Times|date=September 24, 2010}}</ref>

Her essays and reviews have appeared in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', ''[[Harper's]]'', ''[[Playboy]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', and ''[[Bookforum]]''.

==Writings about sexual harassment policies==
In March 2015, after Northwestern University professor [[Peter Ludlow]] had been accused of sexual harassment, Kipnis wrote an essay in the ''[[Chronicle of Higher Education]]'' in which she decried "sexual paranoia" on campuses and discussed professor-student sexual relationships and [[Trauma trigger#Trigger warning|trigger warnings]].<ref>[[#KipnisSexualParanoia|Kipnis, 27 February 2015]]</ref> A group of students at Northwestern protested Kipnis's piece, demanding that the administration reaffirm its commitment to the sexual harassment policies that Kipnis criticized.<ref>[[#GoldbergMelodrama|Goldberg, 16 March 2015]]</ref> In an opinion column for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Northwestern University president [[Morton O. Schapiro]] referred to the protest and argued for maximum speech in such conflicted situations.<ref>[[#MortonUnrest|Morton, 18 March 2015]]</ref> Two students "took issue with the piece, saying Kipnis was describing a real-life scenario and that her facts were off. They accused Kipnis of retaliatory behavior and creating a hostile environment". They filed a complaint with Northwestern's [[Title IX]] office, arguing that her essay had a "chilling effect" on students' ability to report sexual harassment. The school opened an investigation into the case.<ref>Kingkade, Tyler. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/05/31/laura-kipnis-essay-northwestern-title-ix_n_7470046.html "How Laura Kipnis' 'Sexual Paranoia' Essay Caused a Frenzy at Northwestern University"], ''[[Huffington Post]]'', June 1, 2015, accessed May 2, 2017</ref> Kipnis discussed the charges and details of the investigation of those complaints in an essay titled "My Title IX Inquisition," noting that her faculty support person had also been brought up on Title IX complaints over public statements about her case. Northwestern eventually exonerated her.<ref>{{cite news |last=Read |first=Brock |title=Laura Kipnis Is Cleared of Wrongdoing in Title IX Complaints| url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/laura-kipnis-is-cleared-of-wrongdoing-in-title-ix-complaints/99951 |work=Chronicle of Higher Education |date=31 May 2015}}</ref> Title IX complaints were also filed against Northwestern's President Schapiro over his ''Wall Street Journal'' column.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Wilson |first=Robin |date=4 June 2015 |title=For Northwestern, the Kipnis Case Is Painful and Personal |url=http://chronicle.com/article/For-Northwestern-the-Kipnis/230665 |journal=Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref>

Kipnis's 2017 book, ''[[Unwanted Advances: Sexual Paranoia Comes to Campus]]'' discusses the Ludlow case and argues that sexual harassment policies do not empower women and impede the fight for gender equality.<ref>{{cite news |last= Cooke|first= Rachel|date=2 April 2017 |title= Sexual paranoia on campus – and the professor at the eye of the storm |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/02/unwanted-advances-on-campus-us-university-professor-laura-kipnis-interview |work=[[The Observer]] |location= |access-date= }}</ref> One of the students who had brought the Title IX complaints against Ludlow initiated a lawsuit naming Kipnis and her publisher, HarperCollins, and alleging invasion of privacy, defamation, and other charges relating to the book.<ref name=Rhodes1>Rhodes, Dawn. "[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-northwestern-student-sues-professor-book-20170517-story.html Northwestern student sues prof Laura Kipnis over ''Unwanted Advances'' book]", ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', May 17, 2017</ref>

