{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}} {{good article}}
The English musician [[Paul McCartney]] had numerous relationships during his early life in [[Liverpool]] and during his time with [[the Beatles]]. He was engaged to Dot Rhone and actress [[Jane Asher]], and he married three times: to [[Linda McCartney|Linda Eastman]], [[Heather Mills]], and Nancy Shevell.
McCartney had a three-year relationship with Dot Rhone in Liverpool, and bought her a gold ring in [[Hamburg]]. In London, McCartney had a five-year relationship with Asher, and lived in her parents' house for three years. He wrote several songs at the Ashers' house, including "[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]". Asher inspired other songs, such as "[[And I Love Her]]", "[[You Won't See Me]]", and "[[I'm Looking Through You]]". On 25&nbsp;December&nbsp;1967 they announced their engagement, but they separated in early 1968.
McCartney met the American photographer Linda Eastman in a club in London while still with Asher. They met again at the launch party for the Beatles' ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|Sgt. Pepper]]'' album. In May&nbsp;1968, McCartney met Eastman again in New York, and they were married on 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1969. They had three children together and remained married until her death from breast cancer in 1998.
McCartney appeared publicly beside [[Heather Mills]] at a party in January&nbsp;2000, to celebrate her 32nd birthday. On 11&nbsp;June&nbsp;2002, they were married at Castle Leslie in [[Glaslough]], Ireland. They had one child, Beatrice, in 2003 but were living apart by May&nbsp;2006. In July 2006, British newspapers announced that McCartney had petitioned for divorce. On 17&nbsp;March&nbsp;2008, the financial terms of the divorce were finalised, which awarded Mills £24.3 million ($38.5 million). In November&nbsp;2007, McCartney started dating Nancy Shevell, who was a member of the board of the [[New York Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] and is vice president of a family owned [[New England Motor Freight]]. It was announced on 6&nbsp;May&nbsp;2011 that the two had become engaged, and they married in London on 9 October 2011.
==Early relationships== <!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Paul and Dot Rhone.jpg|150px|left|thumb|McCartney and Rhone in 1962]] -->
One of McCartney's first girlfriends, in 1959, was called Layla; a name he remembered as being unusual in Liverpool at the time.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=29}} She was slightly older than McCartney and used to ask him to [[Babysitting|baby-sit]] with her. Julie Arthur, another girlfriend, was [[Ted Ray (comedian)|Ted Ray]]'s niece.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=29}}
McCartney's first serious girlfriend in Liverpool was seventeen year old Dorothy "Dot" Rhone (a bank clerk or a cashier at a chemist's, according to varying accounts),{{sfn|Flippo|1988|p=72}} whom he had met at [[The Casbah Coffee Club|The Casbah Club]] in 1959.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=65}}{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=163}} McCartney picked out the clothes he liked Rhone to wear and told her which make up to use, also paying for her to have her blonde hair done in the style of [[Brigitte Bardot]], whom both he and [[John Lennon]] idolised.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=171}} He disliked Rhone seeing her friends, and stopped her from smoking, even though he did so himself.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=66}} When McCartney first went to Hamburg with The Beatles he wrote regular letters to Rhone, and she accompanied Lennon's girlfriend, [[Cynthia Lennon]] to Hamburg when the group played there again in 1962.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=239–240}} According to Rhone, McCartney bought her a gold ring in Hamburg, a leather skirt, took her sightseeing, and was very attentive and caring.{{sfn|Harry|2002|p=54}}{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=246}} For the time Rhone was there, the couple lived in a bungalow by the Hamburg docks that belonged to Rosa, a former cleaner at the Indra club.{{sfn|Cross|2004|p=33}} McCartney admitted that he had other girlfriends in Hamburg when Rhone was in Liverpool,{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=66}} admitting that they were usually [[Striptease|strippers]], who knew a lot more about sex than Liverpool girls.<ref name="TheBeatlesAnthologyDVDEpisode14351">''The Beatles Anthology'' DVD 2003 (Episode 1: 43:51) McCartney talking about sex and strippers in Hamburg.</ref>
Rhone later rented a room in the same house as Cynthia Lennon was living,{{sfn|Flippo|1988|p=166}} with McCartney contributing to the rent.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=311}} Shortly after McCartney returned from Hamburg in May&nbsp;1962, Rhone told him that she was pregnant. They told McCartney's father, [[Jim and Mary McCartney|Jim McCartney]], whom they expected to be shocked at the news, but found him delighted at the prospect of becoming a grandfather. McCartney took out a marriage licence and set the wedding date for November, shortly before the baby was due.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|pp=319–320}} Rhone had a miscarriage in July&nbsp;1962, and after a few weeks, McCartney's feelings towards Rhone "cooled off", and he finished their relationship.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=348}}
He then had a brief relationship with Thelma Pickles, who had previously dated Lennon. She later married Liverpool poet [[Roger McGough]], but remembered McCartney as growing from a "plump young schoolboy into someone very much his own person" during their time together.{{sfn|Bowen|2008|p=54}} McCartney also had a fiery "on-off" relationship with Iris Caldwell, the younger sister of singer [[Rory Storm]], who refused to bow to McCartney's demands.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=66}} After one argument, Caldwell poured a bowl of sugar over his head, but when McCartney turned up the next day, she had to phone her new boyfriend, [[George Harrison]], to cancel their date.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=67}}
Rhone later emigrated to [[Toronto]], Canada,<ref name="Everybodygotsomethingtohide">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051212/12spitz.htm |title=Everybody's got something to hide, even the Beatles |first=Alex |last=Kingsbury|publisher=[[U.S.News & World Report]] |date=12 December 2005 |accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref> and McCartney met her again when the Beatles played there, and then again with [[Wings (band)|Wings]].<ref name="TripodRhone"/> Rhone later said that "[[Love of the Loved]]" and "[[P.S. I Love You (The Beatles song)|P.S. I Love You]]" were written about her.{{sfn|Cross|2004|p=423}} Years later, Cynthia Lennon gave back to Rhone the gold ring that McCartney had bought her in Hamburg, having once tried it on while Rhone was washing dishes, and forgotten to take it off. Rhone is now a grandmother and lives in [[Mississauga, Ontario]].<ref name="TripodRhone">{{cite web|url=http://sentstarr.tripod.com/beatgirls/rhone.html |title=Dorothy Rhone|publisher=Sentstarr Tripod |accessdate=14 May 2011}}</ref>
==Asher, McGivern, Eastman and Schwartz== [[Image:JaneAsher.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Asher during filming of the [[Maestro (TV series)|''Maestro'' TV series]] in 2008]]
McCartney first met British actress [[Jane Asher]] on 18&nbsp;April&nbsp;1963, when the Beatles performed at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], in London, after a photographer asked them to pose with her.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=101}} They were then interviewed by Asher for the [[BBC]], with Asher being photographed screaming at them like a fan.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=102}} McCartney soon met Asher's family: [[Margaret Eliot|Margaret]], her mother was a music teacher, and Asher's father [[Richard Asher|Richard]] was a physician.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=112}} Her brother, [[Peter Asher|Peter]], was a member of [[Peter and Gordon]], and her younger sister, Clare, was also an actress.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=104}} McCartney later gave "[[A World Without Love]]" to Peter and Gordon, as well as "Nobody I Know". Both songs were hits for the duo.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=112}} McCartney took up residence at the Ashers' house at 57&nbsp;Wimpole&nbsp;Street, London, and lived there for nearly three years.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=106}} During his time there McCartney met writers such as [[Bertrand Russell]], [[Harold Pinter]], and [[Len Deighton]].{{sfn|Miles|1997|pp=125–126}} He wrote several songs at the Ashers', including "Yesterday", and worked on songs with Lennon in the basement music room. Asher inspired many songs, such as "And I Love Her", "You Won't See Me", and "I'm Looking Through You".{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=108}}
On 13&nbsp;April&nbsp;1965, McCartney bought a £40,000 three storey [[Regency architecture|Regency]] house at 7&nbsp;Cavendish&nbsp;Avenue, [[St. John's Wood]], London, and spent a further £20,000 renovating it.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=126}} He thanked the Ashers by paying for the decoration of the front of their house.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=254}} On 15&nbsp;May&nbsp;1967, McCartney met American photographer [[Linda McCartney|Linda Eastman]] at a [[Georgie Fame]] concert at [[The Bag O'Nails]] in London.{{sfn|WingspanDVD|2001}}<ref name="Nails">{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Raymond |date=20 August 2006 |url=http://www.revolverbook.co.uk/beatleslondon.html |title=The Beatles' London, 1965–66 ''Abracadabra!'' |publisher=revolverbook |accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> Eastman was in the UK on an assignment to take photographs of "swinging sixties" musicians in London.<ref>{{cite web |title=Deep Purple Atlas |url=http://www.deep-purple.net/archive/a-z/speakeasy/48-Margaret-St-resizes.jpg |publisher=The Deep Purple Appreciation Society, deep-purple.net |accessdate=11 June 2006}}</ref> They met again four days later at the launch party for the ''Sgt. Pepper'' album at Beatles' manager [[Brian Epstein|Brian Epstein's]] house in [[Belgravia]], but after her assignment was completed, she flew back to New York.{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=117}} On 25&nbsp;December&nbsp;1967, McCartney and Asher announced their engagement, and she accompanied McCartney [[The Beatles in India|to India]] in February and March&nbsp;1968.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=154}}
Dark haired model Maggie McGivern was dating a photographer when, in 1966, she embarked on a secret relationship with McCartney. She had just taken on a steady job working for Marianne Faithfull and John Dunbar as the nanny to their little boy Nicholas, and it was while taking care of Nicholas in Marianne’s third floor Chelsea flat that she first encountered Paul McCartney. He buzzed the intercom to ask if John (Dunbar) was around, and when Paul explained who he was, Maggie invited him straight up. “Paul ran up the stairs and came in. Very casually I told him that John wasn’t really in and that sent us both into hysterics. We were laughing and chatting. I made a nice lunch for Marianne and a bunch of her friends but they never showed up. Paul and I sat together and ate it instead. I’ll never forget the meal – it was chicken casserole. It was such a funny introduction that it threw us both off guard. It could have been very embarrassing, but there was an immediate rapport and we just couldn’t stop talking.” They began a secret three-year affair which ended just before Paul married Linda.<ref>http://beatle-girls.blogspot.co.uk/p/the-girlfriends.html</ref>
Asher broke off the engagement in early 1968, after coming back from an acting assignment in [[Bristol]] to find McCartney in bed with another woman, [[Francie Schwartz]]. McCartney and Asher later attempted to mend their relationship, but finally broke up in July&nbsp;1968. Asher has consistently refused to publicly discuss that part of her life.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchison |first=Amanda |date=3 October 2005 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/10/03/ftjane03.xml |title=Butter wouldn't melt |publisher=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=7 May 2007 | location=London}}</ref>{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=452}} Schwartz, a twenty-three-year-old New York scriptwriter, had travelled to London to interest [[Apple Records|Apple Corps]] in a film script.<ref name="LindaWantsMcCartney">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1303363/Paul-McCartneys-turbulent-love-life-Linda-snare-Beatle--matter-stood-way.html |title=She'd had 20 lovers in two years. Now Linda was out to snare Paul McCartney - no matter who stood in her way|first=Howard |last=Sounes|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]] |date=16 August 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref> Schwartz was then asked by McCartney to move into his [[Cavendish Avenue]] house, and was given a job working for [[Derek Taylor]] at Apple,<ref name="Francietellsall1">{{cite web|url=http://oldies.about.com/cs/theculture/a/schwartz.htm |title=Francie Schwartz: The "White Album girlfriend" tells all |first=Robert |last=Fontenot|first2=Francie |last2=Schwartz| page=1|publisher=[[About.com]] |date= |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> which was then based in [[Wigmore Street]], London.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=160}} She attended many sessions during the recording of the ''[[The Beatles (album)|White Album]]'', and was living with McCartney when Lennon and [[Yoko Ono]] were also invited to live there.<ref name="Francietellsall3">{{cite web|url=http://oldies.about.com/cs/theculture/a/schwartz_3.htm |title=Francie Schwartz: The "White Album girlfriend" tells all |first=Robert |last=Fontenot|first2=Francie |last2=Schwartz| page=3|publisher=[[About.com]] |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> Shortly after, Schwartz sold the story of her time at Cavendish Avenue to ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' magazine.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=169}}
==Marriage to Linda Eastman== [[Image:Paul McCartney with Linda McCartney - Wings - 1976.jpg|200px|thumb|right|The McCartneys in 1976]]
In May&nbsp;1968, McCartney met Eastman again in New York, when Lennon and McCartney were there to announce the formation of Apple Corps.{{sfn|Spitz|2005|p=761}} In September, McCartney phoned her and asked her to fly over to London.{{sfn|Carlin|2009|p=158}} Six months later they were married at a small civil ceremony—when Eastman was four months pregnant with their child, [[Mary McCartney]]—at [[Marylebone]] Registry Office on 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1969. He later said that his wife was the woman who "gave me the strength and courage to work again", after the break-up of the Beatles.<ref name="Sequel">{{cite news |title=Sequel: All Together Now Thirty years later, the surviving Beatles get back to where they once belonged |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=14 February 1994 }}</ref> McCartney adopted her daughter from her first marriage, [[Heather McCartney|Heather]], and had three children together: [[Mary McCartney|Mary]], [[Stella McCartney|Stella]], and [[James McCartney|James]] McCartney.<ref name="StellaTriumphs">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/982824.stm |title=Stella triumphs in New York |date=21 October 2000 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=29 January 2007}}</ref> McCartney taught Linda to play keyboards, and permanently included her in the line-up of [[Wings (band)|Wings]].<ref name="McCartneyWingsIt">{{cite web |first=Ray |last=Bonici |url=http://beatles.ncf.ca/mpl.html |title=Paul McCartney Wings it alone |publisher=Music Express" (Canada) issue #56 (GG70470) |year=1982 |accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref>
Linda died of breast cancer at age 56 in [[Tucson, Arizona]], on 17&nbsp;April&nbsp;1998;<ref name="Linda’sdeath"/> McCartney denied rumours that her death was an [[assisted suicide]].<ref name="Linda’sdeath">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/82362.stm |title=Linda's death |date=23 April 1998 |publisher=BBC News Online|accessdate=29 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/80494.stm |title=Linda McCartney's Obituary |date=19 May 1998 |publisher=BBC News Online|accessdate=29 January 2007}}</ref> Along with eight other British composers, he contributed to the choral album ''[[A Garland for Linda]]'', and dedicated his [[classical music|classical]] album, ''[[Ecce Cor Meum]]'', to his late wife.<ref name="GarlandForLindaBBC">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/345875.stm |title=A Garland for Linda |publisher=BBC News Online|date=17 May 1999|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref> McCartney has said that he and Linda spent less than a week apart during their entire marriage, excluding McCartney's incarceration in [[Tokyo]] on drug charges in January&nbsp;1980.<ref name="StillOnTheRun">{{cite web|url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12049116 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010165133/http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12049116 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=10 October 2008 |title=Still On The Run |first=Gary |last=Graff|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=5 July 2001|accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>
==Marriage to Heather Mills== <!-- Put references into this article or your edit will be deleted -->
After having sparked the interest of the [[popular press|tabloids]] about his appearances at events with former model, amputee, and campaigner against landmines [[Heather Mills]], McCartney appeared publicly beside her at a party in January&nbsp;2000, to celebrate her 32nd birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heathermillsmccartney.com/ |title=Heather Mills web page |accessdate=2 November 2006}}</ref> On 11&nbsp;June&nbsp;2002, McCartney married Mills in an elaborate ceremony at Castle Leslie in Glaslough, [[County Monaghan]], Ireland, where more than 300 guests were invited and the reception included a vegetarian banquet.<ref name="Uebelherr">{{cite news |last=Uebelherr |first=Jan |title=They can't work it out; For these couples, summer wasn't all sunshine |work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |date=21 August 2006 }}</ref> On 28 October 2003,<ref name="HelloHeather">{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/profiles/heathermills/ |title=Heather Mills' Biography|publisher=[[Hello!]] |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> Mills gave birth to a daughter, Beatrice Milly McCartney, although the date has also been stated as 30&nbsp;October.<ref name="MaccaShrink">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/article67924.ece |title=Macca is seeing a shrink |first=Gordon |last=Smart|publisher=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)]] |date=20 October 2006 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> The baby was reportedly named after Mills' mother Beatrice, and McCartney's Aunt Milly.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Larry |title=Legal Analysis of Scott Peterson Preliminary Hearing Day Two; Interview With Paul Burrell|work=[[CNN]] [[Larry King Live]] (transcript) |date=30 October 2003 }}</ref>
On 29&nbsp;July&nbsp;2006, British newspapers announced that McCartney had petitioned for divorce, which sparked a media furore.<ref name="Whitall">{{cite web |last=Whitall |first=Susan |title=Women swoon as Paul McCartney is single again |publisher=[[The Detroit News]] |date=24 May 2006 |url=http://www.ocregister.com/entertainment/-149586--.html |accessdate=29 January 2007}}</ref><ref name="gaggingorder">{{cite web|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/law/article604920.ece |title=My advice to Sir Paul? Pay up now – and get a gagging order |first=Marilyn |last=Stowe|publisher=[[Times Newspapers]] |date=18 October 2006 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> On 17&nbsp;March&nbsp;2008, the financial terms of the divorce were finalised,<ref name="judgment">{{cite news|date=17 March 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/18_03_08_mccartney_mills.pdf|title=Judgment: McCartney and Mills McCartney|accessdate=18 March 2008}}</ref> with a settlement awarding Mills £24.3 million ($38.5 million).<ref name="inaccurateevidence">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7302736.stm |title=Mills gave 'inaccurate' evidence|publisher=BBC News Online|date=18 March 2008 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> The settlement stated that McCartney pay their four-year-old daughter Beatrice's nanny, school fees, and pay Beatrice £35,000 ($70,000) a year until she is 17, or ends her secondary education.<ref name="judgment"/> After the divorce ruling, Justice Bennett said that throughout the case Mills was "inconsistent, inaccurate and less than candid" while McCartney was "honest."<ref name="McCartneywashonest">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/paul-mccartney/35275 |title=Divorce judge: 'Paul McCartney was honest, Heather Mills wasn't'|publisher=[[NME]] |date=18 March 2008 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Heather Mills 'inconsistent, inaccurate witness' in Paul McCartney divorce case |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/?xml=/news/2008/03/18/nmacca518.xml | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | first1=Caroline | last1=Gammell | first2=Matthew | last2=Moore | date=18 March 2008 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> On 12&nbsp;May&nbsp;2008, Justice Hugh Bennett issued a [[decree nisi]], which would become final after a period of six months apart.<ref name="McCartneyandMillsgranteddivorce">{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/05/12/uk-britain-mccartney-idUKL122579520080512 |title=McCartney and Mills granted divorce |first= Avril |last=Ormsby |first2=Paul |last2=Majendie|publisher=Reuters |date=12 May 2008 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref>
==Marriage to Nancy Shevell== <!-- Put references into this article from books or web pages or your edit will be deleted --> McCartney started dating Shevell in November&nbsp;2007. She was a member of the board of the [[New York Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] as well as vice president of a family-owned transportation conglomerate that includes [[New England Motor Freight]].<ref name="VicePresident">{{cite web|url=http://www.nemf.com/nancy.html |title=Nancy Shevell: Vice President – Administration|publisher=[[New England Motor Freight]] |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> She resigned from the MTA board in January 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/183176-blog-paul-mccartneys-wife-nancy-shevell-steps-down-mta-board/|title=Paul McCartney's Wife Nancy Shevell Steps Down From MTA Board|newspaper=WNYC|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> It was announced on 6&nbsp;May&nbsp;2011 that the two had become engaged.<ref name="McCartneyengagedtoNancy">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/paul_mccartney_engaged_to_nancy_L2B7GdLg5Uu2SNE8W8ZvQI?CMP=OTC-rss&FEEDNAME=|title=Beatles legend Paul McCartney engaged to Nancy Shevell|publisher=[[New York Post]] |date=6 May 2011|accessdate=13 May 2011}}</ref> On 9 October 2011 McCartney and Shevell were married at Old Marylebone Town Hall where his first wedding took place in 1969. The couple attended Yom Kippur synagogue services prior to the wedding, out of respect for Shevell's Jewish faith,<ref>{{cite web|author=Danna Hartman & Reuters|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/paul-mccartney-s-new-bride-gets-synagogue-blessing-ahead-of-wedding-1.388971 |title=Paul McCartney’s new bride gets synagogue blessing ahead of wedding |work=Ha'aretz |date=2011-10-09 |accessdate=2015-01-13}}</ref> but did not seek a religious blessing for their union.<ref>{{cite web|author=Simon Rocker |url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/56217/yesterday-paul-mccartney-went-shul |title=Yesterday Paul McCartney went to shul |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2011-10-11 |accessdate=2015-01-13}}</ref> Upon their marriage, Shevell became Lady McCartney.<!--The wife of a knight is Lady Surname--><ref name=BelleNews>{{cite news|last=Walters|first=Judy|title=Nancy Shevell becomes Lady McCartney.|url=http://www.bellenews.com/2011/10/10/entertainment/nancy-shevell-becomes-lady-mccartney/|accessdate=11 October 2011|newspaper=Belle News|date=10 October 2011}}</ref> McCartney wrote the song "My Valentine", from his 2012 album ''[[Kisses on the Bottom]]'', about Shevell. She is a cousin of broadcast journalist [[Barbara Walters]].<ref name="NYOBSERVER">Prince, Daisy, [http://observer.com/2011/08/how-trucker-girl-nancy-shevell-became-lady-mccartney/ "How Trucker-Girl Nancy Shevell Became Lady McCartney: Who is this mystery New Jersey-ite dating Sir Paul?"], ''The New York Observer'', August 2011</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/celebrity/barbara-walters-mccartneys-girlfriend-is-my-cousin/|title=Barbara Walters: McCartney’s Girlfriend Is My Cousin|date=2007-11-12|newspaper=PEOPLE.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref><!-- The media consistently incorrectly report she is Barbara Walters' "second cousin," but Nancy's mother was Barbara's first cousin, making Nancy Barbara's first-cousin-once-removed. The error originated with Barbara herself who, like many/most people, incorrectly thought such a relationship was considered "second cousins." -->
